title: For Sale:  Original Early AMT Backup 380 Tested/Clean/Checked NICE ONE!
postcontent: If you know about these AMT stainless pistols, you know the design lasted from 1976 to the late 90s and guns were made in El Monte, Covina and a few other places and names. The early El Monte guns are referred to as the best as quality control was at its peak before AMT had financial issues. This is the original single action design and the magazine is the original design with the metal finger groove and single witness hole. Again, the best as the ones with plastic finger extensions are iffy. This is a low cost pistol though and not a true collector gun, but some folks just love their pocket pistols. I have owned many of these and the predecessor OMC pistols and I love the all-stainless heavy metal gun feel. It weighs over double the weight of a Ruger LCP but there is NOTHING exciting or cool about those. These look like a shrunken Hardballer (their 45) or a baby Browning scaled up. It has a grip safety and a thumb safety and this one has zero ledge or roughness from feed-ramp to chamber. It has the original brown wood grips and like most (look at the others) the lettering on the slide is faded but still clear and complete.This pistol was disassembled down to every pin, spring and part. Only the bolt was left complete, and every part was cleaned, checked and oiled. I replaced the disconnector spring as it was no good and every other spring and part checks out fine. The bore is perfect as it should be and it is ready to go.Buying this older pistol has no worries as every part is good to go and free of corrosion. You would be surprised what the inner parts of many of these look like as many were pocket carried or tossed around in a drawer or glove box. Thats why the slides show wear but these are all stainless!
